const faqs = [
  { q: 'Does the Apple Magic Keyboard Touch ID work with Windows?', a: 'No. The Touch ID sensor only works on Apple Silicon Macs (M1, M2, M3, and later). On Windows PCs and Intel Macs, the keyboard connects over Bluetooth and types normally, but the fingerprint sensor is inactive. The Touch ID button still functions as a power button on supported Macs even when the sensor is not paired.' },
  { q: 'How long does the Magic Keyboard battery last?', a: 'Apple rates the Magic Keyboard for about a month between charges with typical use. In our testing, with roughly four hours of typing per day and Bluetooth always on, the battery lasted 32 days before needing a recharge. A full charge from empty takes about two hours over the included USB-C to Lightning cable. There is no quick-charge feature, but you can type while charging.' },
  { q: 'Can you use the Magic Keyboard with an iPad?', a: 'Yes. The Magic Keyboard pairs over Bluetooth with any iPad running iPadOS 14 or later, and the typing experience is excellent on iPadOS. The function row shortcuts work for brightness, volume, and media playback. Touch ID does not function on iPad — only on Apple Silicon Macs. For an iPad, the Magic Keyboard is a strong alternative to the iPad Magic Keyboard accessory if you do not need a trackpad.' },
  { q: 'Is the Magic Keyboard good for coding?', a: 'It depends on your preference. The scissor switches are quiet and low-travel, which is fast for typing and friendly to pair-programming environments. However, there is no backlighting, no numpad on the standard model, and no function-key customization. Most developers who code all day will prefer a mechanical keyboard, but the Magic Keyboard is excellent for short bursts of writing, documentation, and email.' },
